Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Trevor W Roussell in court.  Porchia Sharese Lewand appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Petition for Appointment of Counsel and Affidavit of Indigency received and filed. Indigency hearing proceeded.  Court reviewed documents provided by the Defendant.  Statements by the Defendant.  Based upon review of the Defendant's financial documents and statements made in court, the Court finds that the Defendant is indigent and does qualifiy for representation at the County's expense. Court will appoint counsel for Defendant.   Court ordered Defendant to contribute to legal expenses at a rate of  $35.00 per month while this case is pending to which the defendant agreed.  All payments should be made directly to the Clerk of Courts Office.  The court orders defendant to return on 12-14-2015 when counsel will be appointed.  Status conference scheduled for December 14, 2015 at 08:15 am.
